THE COMING OF THE KINGDOM OF GOD (Lk 17: 20-25)<br/><br/>Asked by the Pharisees when the kingdom of God would come, Jesus, said to them in reply, &quot;The coming of the kingdom of God cannot be observed, an no one will announce, 'Look, here it is,' or 'There it is.' For behold, the kingdom of God is among you.&quot; 
<br />Then he said to His disciples, &quot;The days will come when you will long to see one of the days of the Son of Man, but you will not see it. There will be those who will say to you, 'Look, there He is,' or 'Look, here He is.' Do not go off, do not run in pursuit. For just as lightning flashes and lights up the sky from one side to the other, so will the Son of Man be in His day. But first He must suffer greatly and be rejected by this generation.&quot;
<br /><br />Jesus is telling us that the kingdom of God is not coming soon, rather He is telling us &quot;Behold, the kingdom of God is among you.&quot; It is here and right now at this moment. And that If He dwells in our hearts. But why is it that we are still looking for it somewhere else? It is because our hearts and minds are full of malice, bitterness, anger, deceit and so on, that is why, the kingdom of God cannot reign in us for we are overshadowed with the evil forces because of our sinfulness. There are times that we are easily angered by little things that others do, most especially to the members of our family, but wait, if we loose them in our lives, would that be enough to ease our anger? Would we not grieve deeply of loosing them? Think about it, so that when the days will come when you will long to see them but they are no longer around, you would not regret forever? If Jesus is physically here with us right now, will we be the new generation to make Him suffer again and reject Him? Let us think and ask ourselves about it? And renew our ways and say: &quot;The kingdom of God is here.&quot; All we have to do, is to empty ourselves with all the things that holds us from entering into a new life of true happiness, peace and love. A forgiving and loving heart remains after we have learned to empty ourselves from everything that does not belong to God. We have to let go of everything and start receiving the true graces and virtues that Mother Mary pours on us when we have let go of them and these will sustain us and will make us persevere. Always be on guard not to let a single or a little point of entry for sin to rule in our heart. Be pure in mind, body and soul. And the kingdom of God will reign forever in our hearts and anywhere we go, we bring great joy and true peace to others.

THE DAY OF THE SON OF MAN (Lk 17:26-37)<br/><br/>THE DAY OF THE SON OF MAN (Lk 17:26-37)
<br /><br />Jesus said to His disciples, &quot;As it was in the days of Noah, so it will be in the days of the Son of Man; they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage up to the day that Noah entered the ark, and the flood came and destroyed them all. Similarly, as it was in the days of Lot; they were eating, drinking, buying, selling, planting, building; on the day when Lot left Sodom, fire and brimstone rained from the sky to destroy them all. So it will be on the day the Son of Man is revealed. On that day, a person who is on the housetop and whose belongings are in the house must go down to get them, and likewise a person in the field must return to what was left behind. Remember the wife of Lot. Whoever seeks to preserve his life will lose it, but whoever loses it will save it. I tell you, on that night there will be two people in one bed; one will be taken, the other left. And there will be two women grinding meal together; one will be taken, the other left.&quot; They said to Him in reply, &quot;Where, Lord? He said to them, &quot;Where the body is, there also the vultures will gather.&quot;
<br /><br />Jesus is telling us that because of the many material possession that holds us, we cannot focus on the salvation of God. &quot;Eating, drinking, marrying...buying, selling, planting, building...There must be more to life than all these. Life is more than the usual tasks and routines and obligations. We often get lost in earning a living without finding a life. We get swallowed by life's daily tasks, needs and obligations and miss life's celebrations and the beauty of creation. Seeing the beauty of creation reflects the Artists Himself, and that is why there is so much to enjoy in this life and be always connected with our Creator. Live life and offer everything to Jesus through Mary so that we will never miss every detail of it and enjoy it. Enjoy life and learn every lessons that comes along with it. Taste and cherish the moments before they rush to memories. Do not skip the chances or they will skip you. Of the two persons that Jesus referred to in the Gospel, one will enjoy life, while life will pass by the other. 
<br /><br />Everything in this life is good but they are all passing, so let us look beyond this life. Let us not set our minds and hearts on these material possessions we have, for they will control us. And the more we have them, the more we crave for more and the more we become proud. And God does not want that to happen and He can take them anytime He wants to. So instead of being proud, we should be thankful and grateful and that we will learn to acknowledge that everything comes from Him. And without God we are nothing. If we desire only what God desires for us, we will be protected against the snares of evil forces, and we will live a holy life. &quot;Where the body is, there also the vultures will gather.&quot;
